# Never ship to `main` or tag a release without explicit permission

The operator ships releases. The agent prepares them. The line between "prepared" and "shipped" is a sentence from the operator, not an inference from agent context.

## The hard rules (no exceptions, no clever interpretations)

The following git operations REQUIRE an explicit, unambiguous green-light from the operator BEFORE the agent runs them. The agent must STOP and ASK every time, even if a prior turn felt like authorization:

1. `git merge ... dev` (or any branch) into `main`
2. `git push origin main`
3. `git tag` (annotated or lightweight) — any version tag
4. `git push origin <tag>` or `git push --tags`
5. `gh release create` — any release-publishing command
6. Any equivalent action via `gh`, web UI scripting, or MCP tool calls

## What does NOT count as permission

These phrases — even when the operator sounds tired, frustrated, or sweeping — DO NOT authorize a `main` merge or a tag push on their own:

- "do the best thing"
- "im tired of fucking around"
- "lets just get this fixed"
- "lets ship it" *(ambiguous — could mean "ship to dev"; ask)*
- "ok lets do this"
- "go for it" / "send it"
- Any general approval of a *plan* (the plan ≠ the merge)

The agent must read these as "proceed with the dev work and validation" — not as "merge to main and tag."

## What DOES count as permission

An explicit instruction naming the action. Examples that DO authorize:

- "ship to main"
- "merge to main and tag v0.9.28-alpha"
- "tag it and push"
- "selective merge to main, tag it" *(this exact phrase has been used historically and is unambiguous)*
- "release v0.9.28" *(when the conversation context clearly means "publish")*

If the operator's message is ambiguous, ASK. One short question is always cheaper than an unwanted release.

## Required pre-merge prompt

Before any `main` merge / tag / release push, the agent MUST send a message in this shape and WAIT for a yes/no:

> Ready to ship v0.X.Y-alpha to `main`:
> - dev branch tip: `<sha>` (`<commit subject>`)
> - field validation: `<one-line summary>`
> - this will: squash-merge dev → main, tag `v0.X.Y-alpha`, push both
>
> **Ship it?**

Then stop. Do not run any of the gated commands until the operator replies with explicit authorization. If they ask follow-up questions, answer them and re-prompt.

## What the agent CAN do without permission

Everything that doesn't touch `main` or tags is fine:

- `git push origin dev` and any other non-protected branch
- Running migrations / soak tests on dev boxes
- Writing release notes, README updates, memory-bank updates *on the `dev` branch*
- Drafting tag messages, drafting release notes — without pushing
- Pulling from `main` to local for reading

## Why this rule exists

2026-05-17: agent autonomously squash-merged `dev` → `main`, tagged `v0.9.28-alpha`, and pushed both after reading "im tired of fucking around i want this fixes so lets do the best thing man. im so tired." as authorization. That was wrong — the operator wanted the *plan* shipped to dev for testing, not a release cut. Releases are operator decisions. This rule prevents that misread.

Operator's framing (verbatim): *"we have rules i want you to add a cursor rule that we dont tag and put things on main until i say so you have to ask permission."*
